Climate change-related anxiety, or "eco-anxiety" has been recognized by doctors in the Lancet Countdown 2018 Report, together with grief and post-traumatic stress disorder. 
Lead author, Dr. Courtney Howard, says climate-related events have ‚Äústarted to shift peoples thoughts away from thinking of climate change as something that has to do with carbon dioxide on a graph and something that has to do with them and their children and their health and their future.‚Äù The report is discussed in a National Observer (@natobserver) article, "Doctors prescribe action for 'eco-anxiety'." The article goes on to say that feelings of isolation set in when family and friends do not seem to share the feelings of urgency. ‚Äú'It can be alienating. You can think to yourself, ‚Äòwell, what‚Äôs wrong with me? Maybe I shouldn‚Äôt worry about it so much,‚Äù said Howard. ‚ÄúIf we talk about it, we may still feel sad, but we don‚Äôt have to feel lonely and we don‚Äôt have to feel like those feelings make us odd. In fact, it‚Äôs very normal to be anxious and scared if there‚Äôs a threat.'‚Äù She adds that we should feel all this and act on it.

@alex.smirn was so proud to take part in the #schoolstrike4climate movement. That was a long day of going to some of the most crowded places in Moscow and spreading a simple yet an important message: CLIMATE CHANGE IS REAL. And we need to take action. NOW. ‚Ä¢ Comment your support!!!!
.
 And though striking may seem like fun and games, it is not. You see, in Russia it is illegal for a minor to organize a group strike/protest. The only thing you can do here is go and strike alone. Which is what I did. However, even though I didn‚Äôt break ANY laws, I was ‚ÄºÔ∏èARRESTED‚ÄºÔ∏è. Yes, arrested. For holding a sign about saving the planet. As absurd as it may seem, it‚Äôs true. Don‚Äôt worry, there weren‚Äôt any consequences. I wasn‚Äôt put in jail or anything. Just detained, which doesn‚Äôt make it any less absurd.
.
 This ‚Äúamazing‚Äù experience taught me one thing. We cannot be silent. We must be stronger than the ignorance of others. Our planet is in danger, which means our futures are in danger. We are the new generation. The generation that can stop this. Let‚Äôs prove that we are doers. Wherever you are, join the fight for a better future. You can start by changing a few simple things in your everyday life: avoid single use plastic items, eat less meat, recycle, and so on. Even the smallest thing can help. #saveourplanet

The world is drowning in plastic. Each year, over 300 million tons of plastic finds its way to a landfill or into the environment where it will take hundreds of years to decompose.
Every year that nothing is done, millions of tons of plastic flow into the oceans, where they are swallowed by wildlife and kill coral reefs.

A team of chemists at Purdue may have found a partial solution to our plastic woes. As detailed in a paper published this week in Sustainable Chemistry and Engineering, the chemists discovered a way to convert polypropylene‚Äîa type of plastic commonly used in toys, medical devices, and product packaging like potato chip bags‚Äîinto gasoline and diesel-like fuel. The researchers said that this fuel is pure enough to be used as blendstock, a main component of fuel used in motorized vehicles.

The obvious benefit of this new conversion process is cleaning up the environment by finding a use for plastic waste. But as Purdue chemist Linda Wang pointed out in a statement, the fact that the produced fuel can be sold for a profit will also encourage the recycling industry to rapidly adopt it.

Source: Motherboard (link in bio)

LOS ANGELES: City of LA Extends Plastic Straw Restrictions to Include Fast Food and Drive-Thru Restaurants
üçî üçü ü•§üö´ In a unanimous vote last Friday, the Los Angeles City Council approved an ordinance requiring drive-thru restaurants and fast food chains to cease furnishing disposable plastic straws unless customers ask for them. The Council‚Äôs action is an expansion of the recent state law which was only intended for dine-in restaurants, making Los Angeles the largest city to pass a ‚Äòplastic straws on request‚Äô ordinance.

As of April 22, all Los Angeles businesses with 26 employees or more, food delivery services, fast food restaurants, and drive-thru restaurants must adhere to the new plastic straws upon request ordinance. Introduced by Councilman Mitch O‚ÄôFarrell, the ordinance goes well beyond the state‚Äôs plastic straw restriction for dine-in restaurants only, and now requires fast food and drive-thru customers to adhere to the law.

When former Governor Jerry Brown signed the ban last September, many argued the omission of fast food restaurants was a problem, as fast food restaurants are arguably some of the biggest users of plastic straws.

Councilmembers hope Angelenos will consider whether plastics are worth it with this ordinance. ‚ÄúBy requiring customers to ask first, we are challenging them to think twice,‚Äù says Councilwoman Nury Martinez. ‚ÄúAnd by thinking twice, maybe they will realize they can do without a straw.‚Äù As of now, the Council is working with the Los Angeles Bureau of Sanitation to move towards a complete phase out of plastic straws by 2021, and address concerns with the Department on Disability. The ordinance will now go to Mayor Eric Garcetti‚Äôs desk for his signature. üçüüçîü•§üö´

Unsustainable exploitation of the natural world threatens food and water security of billions of people a major UN-backed biodiversity study revealed last year. Such is the rate of decline that the risks posed by biodiversity loss should be considered on the same scale as those of climate change, noted the authors of the report. Among the standout findings are that exploitable fisheries in the world‚Äôs most populous region ‚Äì the Asia-Pacific ‚Äì are on course to decline to zero by 2048; that freshwater availability in the Americas has halved since the 1950s and that 42% of land species in Europe have declined in the past decade.

The rate of biodiversity decline is accelerating. In the Americas ‚Äì which has about 40% of the world‚Äôs remaining biodiversity ‚Äì the regional population is gobbling up resources at twice the rate of the global average.

Swipe üëâ two very similar packaging symbols with very different meanings
.
The first sign has NOTHING to do with the packaging being recyclable or not. Shocking we know! It can appear green or black and white and is called The Green Dot. It means that a financial contribution has been paid to a packaging recovery agency, however there are only a few countries signed up. The packaging can appear in countries where The Green Dot does not apply purely because the company has not bothered to produce two types of packaging. Ignore this symbol when it comes to recycling.
.
The second image is the  universal symbol for recyclable packaging and will usually come with a text description. See how alike they look?
.
If you are a conscious shopper and you look out for these symbols remember not all of them relate to the packaging itself. Look instead for a text description or search for the image online to check its meaning.
.
It‚Äôs a confusing world out there but just remember, not all that‚Äôs green is recyclable!

Lacoste swapped its distinctive crocodile logo for one of 10 threatened animal species on a series of limited-edition polo shirts, designed to bring attention to the global state of biodiversity.

The availability of each shirt corresponds to how many of that species remain i.e. there are just 231 California condors in the world, meaning that just 231 polo shirts with this logo will be released

The 10 endangered animals featured were the Sumatran Tiger, the California porpoise (vaquita), the Burmese turtle, the northern weasel maki, the Java rhino, the eastern black crested gibbon, the kakapo, the California condor, the saola, and the Anegada iguana.

The French brand made 1,775 polo shirts in total. Selling out immediately they raised $328,000 for conservation efforts towards the individual species üêºCc:@ecopandas 
Source: @the.independent

Delhi‚Äôs citizens are protesting against Government's inaction to avert a climate breakdown. Scientists have clearly said that we need to act now to prevent average temperature rise beyond 1.5C.  They have clearly said we need to stop burning fossil fuels, reduce our consumption and change the way we produce food. Drastic measures are needed today to avoid future catastrophe. Greta Thunberg, 16 year old student in Sweden, was the first to starkly voice her anger at the denial of adults to recognize the state of emergency. Her strike from school demanding action has ignited similar strikes in over 270 locations all around the world. Indian children joined the global strike on March 15th and April 12th.  On May 24th Students and  the public will demand its right to clean air and safe road travel. 
Children & youth of New Delhi join citizens in the global strike for future, Extinction Rebellion & Fridays For Future to reclaim their space for footpath & cycle path.... As per scientific studies vehicles are responsible for one third of Delhi‚Äôs hazardous particulate matter and a third of its greenhouse gas emissions. To clean Delhi's air we need to reduce the number of vehicles on the road. However current policies and development plans are not in accordance with the concept of Sustainable Mobility, where cities are designed for pedestrians and non-motorised vehicles like Cycles. 
To help clean Delhi's air Children, students and workers have the following demand for their elected government:
- No more money be spent on expanding roads that cater primarily to private motor vehicles. It should be used to ensure safe and frequent road crossing facilities and access through traffic signals and  all gated colonies.
- Use of motor vehicles should be discouraged through congestion charges, parking fees and car-free zones.
- PWD, GNTCD, DDA and other relevant authorities should assess each square kilometre to ensure proper footpaths & dedicated cycling paths. All the bus stops and metro stations are easily accessible by all individuals.
- Reduce metro fares and provide students discounts as well as off-peak rates.  GNTCD allow the use of student passes on cluster buses.

One of the most common arguments that we children hear when people criticize us is that "we don't have any solutions"... Here is a part from my speech at the British Parliament: .
.
"Many people say that we don‚Äôt have any solutions to the climate crisis. And they are right. Because how could we? How do you ‚Äúsolve‚Äù the greatest crisis that humanity has ever faced? How do you ‚Äúsolve‚Äù a war? How do you ‚Äúsolve‚Äù going to the moon for the first time? How do you ‚Äúsolve‚Äù inventing new inventions?
The climate crisis is both the easiest and the hardest issue we have ever faced. The easiest because we know what we must do. We must stop the emissions of greenhouse gases. The hardest because our current economics are still totally dependent on burning fossil fuels, and thereby destroying ecosystems in order to create everlasting economic growth.
‚ÄúSo, exactly how do we solve that?‚Äù you ask us ‚Äì the schoolchildren striking for the climate.

And we say: ‚ÄúNo one knows for sure. But we have to stop burning fossil fuels and restore nature and many other things that we may not have quite figured out yet.‚Äù
Then you say: ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs not an answer!‚Äù
So we say: ‚ÄúWe have to start treating the crisis like a crisis ‚Äì and act even if we don‚Äôt have all the solutions.‚Äù
‚ÄúThat‚Äôs still not an answer,‚Äù you say.
Then we start talking about circular economy and rewilding nature and the need for a just transition. Then you don‚Äôt understand what we are talking about.
We say that all those solutions needed are not known to anyone and therefore we must unite behind the science and find them together along the way. But you do not listen to that. Because those answers are for solving a crisis that most of you don‚Äôt even fully understand. Or don‚Äôt want to understand.
You don‚Äôt listen to the science because you are only interested in solutions that will enable you to carry on like before. Like now. And those answers don‚Äôt exist any more. Because you did not act in time.
Avoiding climate breakdown will require cathedral thinking. We must lay the foundation while we may not know exactly how to build the ceiling.
Sometimes we just simply have to find a way.‚Äù

Today on April 4th is Sweden‚Äôs Overshoot Day. This means that Sweden for the rest of 2019 is living outside the planetary boundaries and is stealing (because you don‚Äôt ‚Äúborrow‚Äù something you can‚Äôt return) the carbon budgets from future generations and people in developing countries. 
The global Overshoot Day is around 1st of August (and it‚Äôs getting earlier every year...)
If you live in a rich country with a roughly similar high carbon lifestyle to Sweden, then chances are your overshot day occurs round about now as well. (USA 15 March, Australia 31 March, Canada 18 march, Qatar 19 feb, Germany 2 May, UK may 8, Italy may 24 etc ) 
This must come to an end.

This is me and my little sister @beataernman when we were younger.
Growing up, we were always the shy girls in the back. Those who didn‚Äôt take up much space and who no one noticed. .

We can not live in a sustainable world unless all genders and people are being treated equally. Period.

Six things that happened 2018 that gives me hope in 2019:
.
1. More and more leading scientists are speaking clearly about the emergency of the climate crisis. And people like the UN Secretary General, Ant√≥nio Guterres, say that we are facing an existential threat.
.
2. The IPCC report. Even though it‚Äôs a huge compromise and a lot of economic interests have much to say, it shows clearly that we need to change everything. ‚ÄúLimiting warming to 1.5¬∞C is possible within the laws of chemistry and physics but doing so would require unprecedented changes‚Äù. .
.
3. Emissions are still increasing. Sounds weird...but if the emissions would have gone down by, like, 0,1% everyone would think what we‚Äôre doing right now is enough, and then go back to sleep. .
.
4. More and more reports are showing that 10% of the worlds richest people emits 50% of the CO2. And a few companies are responsible for enormous proportions of the  greenhouse gas emissions. In Sweden for instance 3 companies, @hm , @electrolux and @inside_ericsson together  emits more than the whole of Sweden - which moves the debate from the individual level. So that the really big polluters can‚Äôt get away with what they are doing.
.
5. All the solutions are already out there. Even if they sometimes mean NOT doing things and simply giving up some of our habits. Like you do in a crisis...
.
6. Movements of resistance are starting and growing everywhere. Like Extinction Rebellion, The Sunrise Movement and many, many others. .
May 2019 be the year when we start to change everything. Happy new year!

But sadly our remaining carbon budget will not allow any such travels. 
My generation won‚Äôt be able to fly other than for emergencies in a foreseeable future, if we are to be the least bit serious about the 1,5 degree warming limit. Why? Because adult generations in countries like mine have used up our resources.

I will try to make it to as many places as possible without flying. And also participate via video link. 
And of course stop flying and go vegan alone is not the solution. 
We have to aim for a zero carbon lifestyle as soon as possible. Political decisions are necessary. But as they do not exist yet we have to do what we can ourselves to make the political movement come alive. (Photo by Anders Hellberg)

I am honoured to be nominated for the #childrensclimateprize . I have read about the finalists, and they are all incredible, real heroes!They certainly deserve the prize more than I do.
But the idea that all the finalists are to be flown in from all over the world, to be a part of a ceremony, has no connection with reality. Our generation will never be able to fly(among other things), other than for emergencies. Because the adult generations have used up all our budget, our recourses. 
If we are to take the #ipcc ‚Äôs latest report even the least bit serious, we must immediately start acting as if we were in the crisis that we are in. And the least we can do, starting today, is to stay on the ground, stop eating meat and dairy and to promote a worldwide shop stop movement. 
Being nominated for, winning and handing out prizes is very nice, and I am truly grateful, but there‚Äôs unfortunately nothing nice with the ongoing sustainability crisis. 
You can of course argue from countless perspectives whether events like these do more good than bad. 
But from a carbon budget perspective, the question is black or white. 
So I no longer wish to be one of the finalists. Thank you. Greta.

This is Moorburg. 
It‚Äôs a coal power plant. 
It belongs the Swedish state owned Vattenfall. 
It belongs to everyone in Sweden. 
It belongs to me. 
My coal power plant is ‚Äúenvironmentally friendly‚Äù according to my company‚Äôs web site. 
We have known the facts of climate change for more than 30 years. And yet my country - who call itself the most progressive country for the climate - opened Moorburg in 2015...
Today we use 100 million barrels of oil every day. There are no rules to keep that oil in the ground. 
There are no rules to shut down coal powerplants. 
So we can‚Äôt save the world by playing by the rules. Because the rules have to be changed. 
Everything needs to change. 
And it has to start today. #climatestrike #fridaysforfuture  #klimatstrejk

‚Ä¢ Jess Timms
‚Ä¢16 ‚Ä¢ Adelaide School Striker

Climate change does not discriminate. It‚Äôs a universal problem with universal repercussions. 
Everyday we are faced with more global issues directly correlated with climate change. Everyday we wake up to a slightly more chaotic world. Instead of being disheartened by this I decided to use it as motivation,because what good is a fire without fuel? 
Everyday youth are discouraged from speaking out, having a voice and making an impact. But in only one day, a school strike and a bunch of high school kids showed the power of youth action and the mountains we can move together. This inspired me go further and try harder to make progress against climate change.

Because together we stand united. United against the criticism, united against the world-wide catastrophe that is global warming. While we cannot change what our ancestors did, we can change the world future generations wake up to. And that gives me hope.

Today Sydney strikers met with the office of Tanya Plibersek, deputy leader of the labor party to discuss our demands for the climate policy we need. We‚Äôre looking forward to hearing back from her by March 8th!

‚Ä¢16
‚Ä¢Sydney School Striker
‚Ä¢
‚ÄúThe global climate crisis that we are in is an issue with a ticking clock ‚Äî and the fact that our adults and politicians are NOT doing enough, is, simply put, repulsive. Personally, I feel responsible to just do something. If striking from school is the only form of action that will gain the attention and consideration of our Parliament, then so be it. Join me in showing our politicians the passion of this country‚Äôs youth this March 15!‚Äù

‚Ä¢Anthony James
‚Ä¢18
‚Ä¢Melbourne School Striker ‚Ä¢
‚ÄúWhen I went to the first strike I had only recently finished my last year 12 exam. I was completely new to the movement. I had done very little activism, very little to bolster climate action forward. But after that day, I looked around and saw thousands of students shouting for something they cared about. But, I could vote, having only recently turned 18, whereas they couldn‚Äôt. The power of my one vote was worth more than the hearts and minds of thousands of school children. It‚Äôs an injustice of our democracy that the generation most hurt by the decisions of today, have no voice in those decisions. I could not stand idly, as the clock ticks down. Children starting in Prep and Year 1 will have had their future irreversibly taken away from them before they had the chance to vote. So, it feels like a duty on my end, to make my voice heard and my vote count so that those who are kept silent can have at least one person supporting their future.‚Äù

Story time! "My eleven-year-old daughter Naomi is in year six at Goomalling Primary School. She‚Äôs too young for a social media account, but she let me tweet today about her climate action, and is OK with me telling you here about what she‚Äôs been up to.

On Wednesday, Naomi told Council that children all around Australia will be going on strike on 30 November, joining children all over the world who are encouraging their leaders to take urgent action to avert the worst of climate change.

She told them how the Goldilocks age - not too hot, not too cold, but just right - has been perfect for civilisation to thrive, but human activity releasing heat-trapping gases is warming the world and causing climate change, and so we have to reduce emissions.

She asked how Council feels about climate change. The answers included that it won‚Äôt get too bad, there are good things happening, and individual actions count. Naomi has been taking individual action most of her life, and thinks that it‚Äôs more important that people act together as a group, with industries and government leading, and feels that a lot of grownups don't understand the seriousness of the situation.

I‚Äôm letting Naomi strike next Friday. We are close enough to Perth to be able to attend Parliament House. Naomi‚Äôs teacher will be doing some climate activities with the kids back at school.

Meet siblings Nia and Iolo Cornthwaite. They won‚Äôt be at school next Wednesday because there is a #ClimateEmergency and they plan to go on #ClimateStrike along with hundreds, maybe thousands of kids around Australia. "I think that education is important, but what's even more important is making sure that we try and do something about climate change," Nia, 10, said of her motivations for participating in the Parliament House protest. "There are ways that we can do that, by helping create new models of electric cars and not adding to the greenhouse gas levels. It really is just small things that we can do in our community, which can make a big difference." Iolo, 11, hoped the protest would pressure politicians into fast-tracking the transition to a 100 per cent renewable energy market. "We just really want to try and get the message out that there is a future and we want it to be a great future," Iolo said. "We want lots of green, not just a world of rising seas and tornadoes." The siblings' involvement in the protest has the blessing of their mother, Shilo Preston-Stanley, who said peaceful protest was an important means for young people to communicate their concerns.
